   =20
      FTX is back!?
   =20
 =20

The   basic situation at FTX Trading Ltd. is that a lot of people =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0retail customers but also institutional crypto traders =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0seem to have liked trading on FTX, but then FTX, and its affiliated trad=
ing firm Alameda Research,=C2=A0lost and/or stole their money. Hearing rumo=
rs of this, FTX=E2=80=99s customers asked to withdraw their money; the mone=
y wasn=E2=80=99t there, and FTX filed for bankruptcy.
So that=E2=80=99s where we are now. How do you=C2=A0fix=C2=A0this? An obvio=
us place to focus is on finding the money and putting it back. If FTX/Alame=
da stole a bunch of customer money and used it to buy Bahamas condos and ma=
ke political and philanthropic donations, you sell the condos and ask for t=
he donations back. If you do that really efficiently, you get all the money=
 back, and you give it back to the customers, and everything is fine. But t=
his seems unlikely to be a complete success. For one thing, you probably wo=
n=E2=80=99t recover all the money, and you=E2=80=99ll have costs in doing s=
o. But also a lot of the money seems to have gone into investments, particu=
larly cryptocurrency investments, that lost a lot of value: If Alameda took=
 $1 billion of FTX customer funds and spent it on magic beans, and you are =
able to sell the magic beans for $35, then that=E2=80=99s $999,999,965 of c=
ustomer money that you=E2=80=99re not getting back.
  [1]
 FTX=E2=80=99s and Alameda=E2=80=99s   financial statements are   notorious=
ly a mess, so I am not quite sure how much customer money went to real esta=
te and donations, how much went to depreciated magic beans, and how much is=
 still sitting in bank accounts. But my guess is that the beans vastly outw=
eigh the real estate, so selling the real estate is not really going to fil=
l the hole.
But there is another, weirder way to fix the problem, which is to pretend i=
t never happened. The proximate cause of FTX=E2=80=99s bankruptcy is not th=
at Alameda borrowed a lot of FTX customer money and lost/stole it. The prox=
imate cause is that=C2=A0people noticed, and asked for their money back. An=
d the money wasn=E2=80=99t there, because it was lost/stolen. But if they h=
adn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0asked=C2=A0for it, they could have blithely continued al=
ong, trading on FTX, racking up profits and losses in their FTX accounts. =
=E2=80=9CI have a billion dollars in my account on FTX,=E2=80=9D a big cust=
omer could have thought, even if FTX didn=E2=80=99t have any actual money b=
acking that account. And then the customer could have kept trading to try t=
o turn that billion dollars into two billion dollars, and as long as it sta=
yed within FTX it wouldn=E2=80=99t matter if there were any actual dollars =
there.
  [2]

=E2=80=9COf course this can=E2=80=99t go on forever,=E2=80=9D one is tempte=
d to say, but can=E2=80=99t it? In the general run of Ponzi schemes it most=
ly can=E2=80=99t, but in, like, late October 2022 =E2=80=94=C2=A0just befor=
e FTX imploded =E2=80=94=C2=A0it was not=C2=A0crazy=C2=A0to think it could =
work for FTX. The theory is:
=09FTX was making a lot of real money, legitimately,
  [3]
=C2=A0by charging fees to traders. If people kept trading and FTX kept accu=
mulating profits, perhaps over time the profits would be enough to fill the=
 hole caused by Alameda=E2=80=99s borrowing/loss/theft.=09At least a large =
part of the hole was caused by Alameda using FTX customer money to buy cryp=
tocurrencies that went down, and maybe they=E2=80=99d go up again! You neve=
r know. And then Alameda could pay back the money and there=E2=80=99d be no=
 more hole.=09More specifically, a large part of the hole seems to have bee=
n caused by Alameda using FTX customer money to fund its   holdings of magi=
c beans that were=C2=A0created by FTX, and that represented essentially a b=
et on FTX=E2=80=99s continuing popularity and success. Tokens like FTT, SRM=
 and MAPS operated sort of like stock in FTX and its related businesses. Wh=
en people got nervous about FTX and Alameda, those tokens lost value, and w=
hen FTX filed for bankruptcy, those basically-stock-in-FTX tokens became ba=
sically worthless. But if it had continued along being popular and successf=
ul, they might have recovered a lot of value, which might have filled the h=
ole.

I don=E2=80=99t want to suggest that this would have been legal, or a good =
idea. Imagine that you were magically installed as chief executive officer =
of FTX in, say, late October of 2022, after Alameda borrowed/lost/stole bil=
lions of dollars of customer money, but before people noticed and demanded =
their money back. And your staff came to you and described the whole situat=
ion in accurate detail, and then asked you what you wanted to do. Your basi=
c choices were:
=09Announce =E2=80=9Chey, turns out the previous management misplaced billi=
ons of dollars of customer money, we=E2=80=99re looking into it, sorry abou=
t that.=E2=80=9D And then try to fill the hole as rapidly as possible =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0by selling cryptocurrency or real estate, by begging to take ba=
ck donations, by finding new outside investors, etc.=C2=A0=09Announce =E2=
=80=9CFTX is stronger than ever,=E2=80=9D reassure customers that everythin=
g is great,=C2=A0and launch=C2=A0a new ad campaign to attract more deposits=
.

Knowing what you hypothetically knew, Option 2 would be terrible terrible f=
raud and probably land you in prison,=C2=A0unless it worked. If it worked =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0if people believed you, they kept blithely trading, the magi=
c beans recovered their value, and you earned enough profits to fill the ho=
le =E2=80=94=C2=A0then, uh, then it would still be fraud, but maybe no one =
would give you too much trouble about it.
  [4]

Would it have worked? I mean, look, we know the answer to that, because it=
=E2=80=99s what FTX=E2=80=99s and Alameda=E2=80=99s actual management did. =
When Coindesk  reported that Alameda=E2=80=99s balance sheet was made up mo=
stly of magic beans, and when Binance CEO Changpeng Zhao  announced that he=
