One important use case of crypto is online crime. If you want to pay for dr=
ugs or assassinations, or get a ransom payment for hacking someone=E2=80=99=
s computer, Bitcoin has some really nice properties. It can be transferred =
anonymously, more or less instantly, over the internet, with no intermediar=
ies =E2=80=94=C2=A0banks, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0that might block or reverse a=
 payment. It has a value that is widely accepted internationally. It is, in=
 many ways,=C2=A0money, but free of the regulation that applies to dollars =
and euros and most other kinds of money.
The only problem is turning your regular money (dollars, euros, rubles, wha=
tever =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cfiat,=E2=80=9D crypto people call it) into Bi=
tcoin, and your Bitcoin back into regular money. Most people have jobs that=
 pay them in fiat currencies, and pay most of their expenses in fiat curren=
cies. If you got your=C2=A0paycheck and want to buy drugs with Bitcoin, or =
if you got a big ransomware payment in Bitcoin and want to buy groceries, y=
ou will need to turn fiat into Bitcoin or Bitcoin into fiat.
And=C2=A0that=E2=80=99s=C2=A0where they get you. All the stuff about Bitcoi=
n =E2=80=94=C2=A0it being anonymous, irreversible, no intermediaries, no na=
tional borders =E2=80=94=C2=A0is not true of the transaction where you turn=
 your fiat into Bitcoin or vice versa.=C2=A0There, you need to hook up a ba=
nk account or a credit card or whatever to transfer your fiat currency into=
 the Bitcoin system.
Crypto exchanges are generally in the business of providing this fiat on/of=
f-ramp service. You open an account at a crypto exchange, you give it your =
bank information, you put in dollars to buy Bitcoin, you sell Bitcoin to ge=
t dollars, and the exchange is the doorway between the dollar financial sys=
tem and the Bitcoin financial system.
This is a fraught business for the exchange to be in. On one side, the side=
 where it is making and accepting fiat payments, it is connected to a regul=
ated banking system, and in the US and many other countries banks have obli=
gations to prevent financial crime. The banks have know-your-customer/anti-=
money-laundering obligations; they try to know who their customers are and =
where their money comes from and what it=E2=80=99s being used for, to try t=
o prevent it being used for crime. In practice, this often means that banks=
 and credit card companies won=E2=80=99t let you send money to a crypto exc=
hange unless the crypto exchange is itself regulated by national authoritie=
s and does its own KYC/AML checks to prevent its customers from using crypt=
o for crime.
  [6]

But on the other side, the side where it is trading crypto, the exchange is=
 connected to the crypto system, and obviously the exchange has lots of cus=
tomers who have lots of reasons for using that system, but, again, one impo=
rtant=C2=A0use case is crime. Presumably the people who want to use Bitcoin=
 for crime will not actually be customers of an upstanding regulated exchan=
ge that does lots of KYC/AML, but they will want to be customers of=C2=A0so=
me=C2=A0exchange. There is a lot of customer demand for a crypto exchange t=
hat is crime-friendly. If you set up a crypto exchange with the goal of bei=
ng crime-friendly, and you develop a reputation for being crime-friendly, y=
ou will win a lot of business.=C2=A0
Of course there are problems. One is: The whole point of this business is t=
hat your crypto exchange has to be able to get money from banks and send mo=
ney back to banks, and how are you going to convince banks to connect=C2=A0=
to your exchange? Most banks in the US and many other countries want to dea=
l with regulated crypto exchanges with good KYC/AML policies. You need to w=
alk a fine line; you need to have a reputation=C2=A0among customers=C2=A0fo=
r being crime-friendly but a reputation=C2=A0among bankers=C2=A0for stoppin=
g crime.
The other problem is of course that   you=E2=80=99ll eventually get arreste=
d:

