       =20
  [1] Well. If Alameda bought the magic beans for $1 billion from some iden=
tifiable counterparty, maybe you could call *them* up and say =E2=80=9Chey =
that was kind of a raw deal, why don=E2=80=99t you give us back the billion=
 dollars and we=E2=80=99ll give you back the beans.=E2=80=9D And if the cou=
nterparty seems to have been, in some sense, in on it =E2=80=94 if Alameda =
bought the beans from, like, an FTX executive, or from some crypto project =
that it incubated =E2=80=94 then maybe that=E2=80=99ll work, as a matter of=
 bankruptcy law or public pressure or whatever. But it seems like a lot of =
this was Alameda buying magic beans from regular traders on crypto exchange=
s in market transactions,  and the odds of clawing back the purchase price =
in those transactions are basically zero.


  [2] Of course sometimes they would withdraw money, and FTX would have to =
give it to them, but the point is that FTX had plenty of money to cover ord=
inary-course withdrawals, just not enough to cover a =E2=80=9Crun on the ba=
nk=E2=80=9D where a lot of people wanted their money back at once. It had e=
nough money to keep going if people were confident in it, but not enough on=
ce they lost confidence.


  [3] This is actually a debatable point. Clearly FTX was intermediating re=
al trades and charging real fees for them, and people were doing these trad=
es because they liked the service and prices they got on FTX. But   there i=
s an argument that customers did these trades specifically because they lik=
ed the *prices*, and they liked the prices specifically because Alameda was=
 on the other side of them and was losing money to subsidize trading on FTX=
. This would be sort of a Ponzi-scheme story of FTX: Alameda stole customer=
 money in order to give other customers the illusion of getting good return=
s on FTX, in order to encourage customers to deposit more money. Sam Bankma=
n-Fried has  posted charts showing that Alameda was a small portion of FTX =
volume, which would mean that =E2=80=9CAlameda subsidized trading prices by=
 stealing customer money and losing it=E2=80=9D is not the main story of FT=
X=E2=80=99s success, but you don=E2=80=99t have to believe Bankman-Fried=E2=
=80=99s charts.


  [4] Oh boy is that not legal advice but, I mean, in crypto, and in tech g=
enerally, =E2=80=9Cfake it till you make it=E2=80=9D seems to have a pretty=
 high success rate. If you make it! If you don=E2=80=99t, people tend to th=
ink that your faking it was fraud.


  [5] Again, the finances are a mess, but this week  FTX reported having $5=
29 million of FTT tokens based on prices =E2=80=9Cas of the Petition Date.=
=E2=80=9D The price of FTT fluctuated a lot on Nov. 11, 2022, the day that =
FTX filed for bankruptcy, from the low $2s to the low $3s, so I don=E2=80=
=99t know how many tokens that represents, but it=E2=80=99s in the neighbor=
hood of like 175 million to 200 million maybe. FTT traded at about $1.81 to=
day before Ray=E2=80=99s announcement, and $2.38 after, so it gained about =
57 cents per token, or around $100 million for FTX=E2=80=99s stash.


  [6] Or unless the crypto exchange is pretty sneaky.  One problem at FTX i=
s that it took some $8 billion of customer deposits through an account for =
Alameda, and one possible explanation of that, in the early days, banks wou=
ldn=E2=80=99t let people send money to FTX, because crypto exchanges are sc=
ary, but =E2=80=9CAlameda Research=E2=80=9D sounded less threatening.


  [7] A funny but *VERY RISKY* way to run a crime-friendly Bitcoin exchange=
 would be to (1) lean heavily into advertising how crime-friendly you are, =
(2) accept deposits without KYC/AML, and (3) never give back the money. Wha=
t are they gonna do, sue you for the money? The money is from crime. But of=
 course if your business is stealing money from criminals, that =E2=80=A6 s=
eems =E2=80=A6 bad =E2=80=A6 for non-legal reasons.


