<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">FTX is back!?</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/30300607.279512/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMTMvaG93LXRvLWRvLWZyYXVkLWF0LWEtZnV0dXJlcy1leGNoYW5=
nZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTE5MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2=
U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAxMTkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB363319c5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  basic situation</a> at FTX Trading =
Ltd. is that a lot of people =E2=80=94=C2=A0retail customers but also insti=
tutional crypto traders =E2=80=94=C2=A0seem to have liked trading on FTX, b=
ut then FTX, and its affiliated trading firm Alameda Research,=C2=A0lost an=
d/or stole their money. Hearing rumors of this, FTX=E2=80=99s customers ask=
ed to withdraw their money; the money wasn=E2=80=99t there, and FTX filed f=
or bankruptcy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So that=E2=80=99s where we are now. How do you=
=C2=A0<em>fix=C2=A0</em>this? An obvious place to focus is on finding the m=
oney and putting it back. If FTX/Alameda stole a bunch of customer money an=
d used it to buy Bahamas condos and make political and philanthropic donati=
ons, you sell the condos and ask for the donations back. If you do that rea=
lly efficiently, you get all the money back, and you give it back to the cu=
stomers, and everything is fine. But this seems unlikely to be a complete s=
uccess. For one thing, you probably won=E2=80=99t recover all the money, an=
d you=E2=80=99ll have costs in doing so. But also a lot of the money seems =
to have gone into investments, particularly cryptocurrency investments, tha=
t lost a lot of value: If Alameda took $1 billion of FTX customer funds and=
 spent it on magic beans, and you are able to sell the magic beans for $35,=
 then that=E2=80=99s $999,999,965 of customer money that you=E2=80=99re not=
 getting back.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgroun=
d-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> FTX=E2=80=99s and Alameda=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/30300607.279512/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9v=
cGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTQvZnR4LXMtYmFsYW5jZS1zaGVldC13YXMtYmFkP2N=
tcGlkPUJCRDAxMTkyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZX=
dzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDExOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB582edc0e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">  financial statements</a> are <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30300607.279512/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTcvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUt=
cy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1mdHgtd2FzLW5vdC12ZXJ5LWNhcmVmdWw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDExOTIzX01=
PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm=
09MjMwMTE5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf81aa59=
d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  notoriously a mess</a>, so I am not quite sure how much cust=
omer money went to real estate and donations, how much went to depreciated =
magic beans, and how much is still sitting in bank accounts. But my guess i=
s that the beans vastly outweigh the real estate, so selling the real estat=
e is not really going to fill the hole.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is another, weirder way to fix the p=
roblem, which is to pretend it never happened. The proximate cause of FTX=
=E2=80=99s bankruptcy is not that Alameda borrowed a lot of FTX customer mo=
ney and lost/stole it. The proximate cause is that=C2=A0<em>people noticed<=
/em>, and <em>asked for their money back</em>. And the money wasn=E2=80=99t=
 there, because it was lost/stolen. But if they hadn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>ask=
ed=C2=A0</em>for it, they could have blithely continued along, trading on F=
TX, racking up profits and losses in their FTX accounts. =E2=80=9CI have a =
billion dollars in my account on FTX,=E2=80=9D a big customer could have th=
ought, even if FTX didn=E2=80=99t have any actual money backing that accoun=
t. And then the customer could have kept trading to try to turn that billio=
n dollars into two billion dollars, and as long as it stayed within FTX it =
wouldn=E2=80=99t matter if there were any actual dollars there.<a class=3D"=
footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impo=
rtant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9COf course this can=E2=80=99t go on fo=
rever,=E2=80=9D one is tempted to say, but can=E2=80=99t it? In the general=
 run of Ponzi schemes it mostly can=E2=80=99t, but in, like, late October 2=
022 =E2=80=94=C2=A0just before FTX imploded =E2=80=94=C2=A0it was not=C2=A0=
<em>crazy=C2=A0</em>to think it could work for FTX. The theory is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">FTX was making a lot of real money, le=
gitimately,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-c=
olor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0by charging fees to traders. If people kept trading and FTX kept =
accumulating profits, perhaps over time the profits would be enough to fill=
 the hole caused by Alameda=E2=80=99s borrowing/loss/theft.</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">At least a large part of the hole was caused by A=
lameda using FTX customer money to buy cryptocurrencies that went down, and=
 maybe they=E2=80=99d go up again! You never know. And then Alameda could p=
ay back the money and there=E2=80=99d be no more hole.</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">More specifically, a large part of the hole seems to h=
ave been caused by Alameda using FTX customer money to fund its <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30300607.279512/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTQvZnR4LXMtYmFsYW5j=
ZS1zaGVldC13YXMtYmFkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMTkyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1=
haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDExOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW=
9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC582edc0e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  holdings of magic=
 beans that were=C2=A0<em>created by FTX</em></a>, and that represented ess=
entially a bet on FTX=E2=80=99s continuing popularity and success. Tokens l=
ike FTT, SRM and MAPS operated sort of like stock in FTX and its related bu=
sinesses. When people got nervous about FTX and Alameda, those tokens lost =
value, and when FTX filed for bankruptcy, those basically-stock-in-FTX toke=
ns became basically worthless. But if it had continued along being popular =
and successful, they might have recovered a lot of value, which might have =
filled the hole.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t want to suggest that this woul=
d have been legal, or a good idea. Imagine that you were magically installe=
d as chief executive officer of FTX in, say, late October of 2022, <em>afte=
r </em>Alameda borrowed/lost/stole billions of dollars of customer money, b=
ut <em>before </em>people noticed and demanded their money back. And your s=
taff came to you and described the whole situation in accurate detail, and =
then asked you what you wanted to do. Your basic choices were:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Announce =E2=80=9Chey, turns out the =
previous management misplaced billions of dollars of customer money, we=E2=
=80=99re looking into it, sorry about that.=E2=80=9D And then try to fill t=
he hole as rapidly as possible =E2=80=94=C2=A0by selling cryptocurrency or =
real estate, by begging to take back donations, by finding new outside inve=
stors, etc.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Announce =E2=80=
=9CFTX is stronger than ever,=E2=80=9D reassure customers that everything i=
s great,=C2=A0and launch=C2=A0a new ad campaign to attract more deposits.</=
li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Knowing what you hypothetically knew, Option 2=
 would be terrible terrible fraud and probably land you in prison,=C2=A0<em=
>unless it worked</em>. If it worked =E2=80=94=C2=A0if people believed you,=
 they kept blithely trading, the magic beans recovered their value, and you=
 earned enough profits to fill the hole =E2=80=94=C2=A0then, uh, then it wo=
uld still be fraud, but maybe no one would give you too much trouble about =
it.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tr=
ansparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Would it have worked? I mean, look, we know th=
e answer to that, because it=E2=80=99s what FTX=E2=80=99s and Alameda=E2=80=
=99s actual management did. When Coindesk <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/30300607.279512/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY29pbmRlc2suY29tL2J=
1c2luZXNzLzIwMjIvMTEvMDIvZGl2aXNpb25zLWluLXNhbS1iYW5rbWFuLWZyaWVkcy1jcnlwdG=
8tZW1waXJlLWJsdXItb24taGlzLXRyYWRpbmctdGl0YW4tYWxhbWVkYXMtYmFsYW5jZS1zaGVld=
C8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB058c5a18" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> reported</a> that Alameda=E2=
=80=99s balance sheet was made up mostly of magic beans, and when Binance C=
EO Changpeng Zhao <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
30300607.279512/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9jel9iaW5hbmNlL3N0YXR1cy8xNTg5Mjg=
zNDIxNzA0MjkwMzA2/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB45038cd6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> announced</a>=
 that he would dump his stash of FTT tokens, FTX CEO Sam Bankman-Fried and =
Alameda CEO Caroline Ellison tweeted confidently about how strong their bal=
ance sheets were and how safe customer money was. They leaned into Option 1=
. It did not work. No one believed them, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/30300607.279512/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9v=
cGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDkvYmFua21hbi1mcmllZC1zLWZ0eC1oYWQtYS1kZWF=
0aC1zcGlyYWwtYmVmb3JlLWJpbmFuY2UtZGVhbD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTE5MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRi=
Z1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAxMTkmd=
XRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe8617e93" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  there was a run</a>, and FTX went bankrupt. Maybe you, in this hypothetic=
al, could have done better, but I wouldn=E2=80=99t count on it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Option 1 would leave you blameless: You came i=
n as the new CEO, you spotted the fraud, you reported it. You didn=E2=80=99=
t deceive anyone; you were honest and open about the problems and moved rap=
idly to fix them. But of course by announcing the problems you will=C2=A0<e=
m>definitely=C2=A0</em>cause a run: If customer money is missing, why shoul=
d customers keep their money at FTX? If FTX is doing fraud and has a net wo=
rth of negative billions of dollars, why should outside investors put in mo=
ney to keep it afloat? Once you have announced the problems, you can=E2=80=
=99t really get customers to ignore them, and getting customers to ignore t=
he problems was the easiest way to solve them. So you are left with the sec=
ond-best way to solve them, which is selling the real estate and magic bean=
s at auction and giving customers whatever you can get.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In fact a new CEO, John J. Ray III,=C2=A0<em>w=
as=C2=A0</em><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30300=
607.279512/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYWNlci1kb2N1bWVudHMuczMuYW1hem9uYXdzLmNvbS8zMy8xODg0=
NTAvMDQyMDIwNjQ4MTk3LnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe90eb51c" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">insta=
lled at FTX</a> =E2=80=9Cin the early morning hours of November 11, 2022,=
=E2=80=9D and he leaned hard into Option 1. He=C2=A0filed for bankruptcy mo=
ments after being installed as CEO, and=C2=A0has been telling everyone abou=
t <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30300607.279512/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTcvbWF=
0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1mdHgtd2FzLW5vdC12ZXJ5LWNhcmVmdWw_Y21waWQ9Qk=
JEMDExOTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0Z=
XImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTE5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cCf81aa59d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  how bad FTX=E2=80=99s governance and finances wer=
e</a>=C2=A0and how it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/30300607.279512/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjMtMDEtMTgvc2xpY2luZy1jYXNoLWZsb3dzLWZvci1iZXR0ZXItcmF0aW5ncz9jbXBpZD=
1CQkQwMTE5MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xld=
HRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAxMTkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB42d16c71" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">  built systems to defraud customers</a>. Meanwh=
ile he is trying to round up FTX=E2=80=99s assets to divvy up among custome=
rs and other creditors. It is still early days, but it is pretty clear that=
 (1) he won=E2=80=99t find enough cash and real estate and magic beans to m=
ake the customers whole and (2) he=E2=80=99s expensive, so as time goes by =
there will be less money for creditors because more will go to him and his =
team.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But can you =E2=80=A6=C2=A0can you =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0can you just a=C2=A0<em>little=C2=A0</em>bit go back to Option 2? Not=
 really, of course; not=C2=A0<em>fraud</em>. You have to be open and honest=
 about the hole in the balance sheet, about the backdoors in FTX=E2=80=99s =
code that allowed Alameda to take all the money. But before they knew about=
 the missing money,=C2=A0a lot of people =E2=80=94=C2=A0retail customers bu=
t also institutional crypto traders =E2=80=94=C2=A0seem to have liked tradi=
ng on FTX, and that is what made FTX valuable, and maintaining and increasi=
ng that value seems like the best way to fill the hole in the balance sheet=
. If FTX could just restart its exchange business, and go back to being pop=
ular and making billions of dollars in trading fees, then those billions of=
 dollars could be used to pay back customers. And if that happened then may=
be the FTT tokens, the magic beans that right now FTX will have trouble sel=
ling, could recover their value, and also be used to pay back customers.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This seems far-fetched and I do not personally=
 have any idea how you could restart trading on FTX, attract new deposits, =
and get everyone to pretend everything is fine so you can earn back the mon=
ey that Alameda borrowed/lost/stole. But I guess John Ray does? The <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30300607.279512/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9uZXctZnR4LWNoaWVmLXNheXMtY3J5cHRvLWV4Y2hhbmdl=
LWNvdWxkLXJlc3RhcnQtMTE2NzQxNDMxNjg_bW9kPWhwX2xlYWRfcG9zMw/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB41583bde" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> Wall Street Journal reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">FTX=E2=80=99s new chief executive, John J. Ray=
 III, said he=E2=80=99s looking into the possibility of reviving the bankru=
pt crypto exchange as he works to return money to the failed company=E2=80=
=99s customers and creditors. =C2=A0=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In his first interview since taking over FTX i=
n November, Mr. Ray said that he has set up a task force to explore restart=
ing FTX.com, the company=E2=80=99s main international exchange. Although to=
p FTX executives have been accused of criminal misconduct, some customers h=
ave praised its technology and suggested that there would be value in reboo=
ting the platform, he said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CEverything is on the table,=E2=80=9D =
Mr. Ray said. =E2=80=9CIf there is a path forward on that, then we will not=
 only explore that, we=E2=80=99ll do it.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Ray said he would look into whether revivi=
ng FTX=E2=80=99s international exchange would recover more value for the co=
mpany=E2=80=99s customers than his team could get from simply liquidating a=
ssets or selling the platform.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThere are stakeholders we=E2=80=99re =
working with who=E2=80=99ve identified what they see is a viable business,=
=E2=80=9D he said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess? I mean, conceptually, what you have t=
o do here is convince big crypto investors to start trading again on FTX by=
 (1) opening up some new entity where they can deposit money that won=E2=80=
=99t get thrown into the hole caused by Alameda and (2) convincing those in=
vestors that, this time, you won=E2=80=99t steal the money. I suppose insta=
lling a new CEO, filing for bankruptcy, and disclosing the hole in the bala=
nce sheet and the backdoors in the code is a way to build that sort of trus=
t. Maybe John Ray had to burn FTX down to save it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/30300607.279512/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2F=
ydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMTkvZnR4LXRva2VuLWp1bXBzLWFmdGVyLW5ldy1jZW8tc2F5cy1leG=
NoYW5nZS1jb3VsZC1yZXN0YXJ0P2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMTkyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpd=
W09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDExOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFp=
Z249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb6902134" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">maybe it=E2=
=80=99s=C2=A0working</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">FTX=E2=80=99s controversial FTT token surged b=
y more than 30% after the bankrupt company=E2=80=99s new chief executive, J=
ohn J. Ray III, said that he=E2=80=99s exploring the possibility of restart=
ing the crypto exchange. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Data from TradingView shows that FTT rose by m=
ore than 30% on rival exchange Binance. FTT was trading at around $2.38 on =
Thursday. That=E2=80=99s still down more than 97% from its record high of $=
84.18, according to pricing data from CoinGecko.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Given FTX=E2=80=99s stash of FTT, that=E2=80=
=99s like $100 million more for creditors right there, just from announcing=
 it.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: t=
ransparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Imagine if it works!</p>
