<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Customer service</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One important use case of crypto is online cri=
me. If you want to pay for drugs or assassinations, or get a ransom payment=
 for hacking someone=E2=80=99s computer, Bitcoin has some really nice prope=
rties. It can be transferred anonymously, more or less instantly, over the =
internet, with no intermediaries =E2=80=94=C2=A0banks, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
that might block or reverse a payment. It has a value that is widely accept=
ed internationally. It is, in many ways,=C2=A0<em>money</em>, but free of t=
he regulation that applies to dollars and euros and most other kinds of mon=
ey.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The only problem is turning your regular money=
 (dollars, euros, rubles, whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cfiat,=E2=80=9D c=
rypto people call it) into Bitcoin, and your Bitcoin back into regular mone=
y. Most people have jobs that pay them in fiat currencies, and pay most of =
their expenses in fiat currencies. If you got your=C2=A0paycheck and want t=
o buy drugs with Bitcoin, or if you got a big ransomware payment in Bitcoin=
 and want to buy groceries, you will need to turn fiat into Bitcoin or Bitc=
oin into fiat.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And=C2=A0<em>that=E2=80=99s=C2=A0</em>where th=
ey get you. All the stuff about Bitcoin =E2=80=94=C2=A0it being anonymous, =
irreversible, no intermediaries, no national borders =E2=80=94=C2=A0is not =
true of the transaction where you turn your fiat into Bitcoin or vice versa=
.=C2=A0<em>There</em>, you need to hook up a bank account or a credit card =
or whatever to transfer your fiat currency into the Bitcoin system.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crypto exchanges are generally in the business=
 of providing this fiat on/off-ramp service. You open an account at a crypt=
o exchange, you give it your bank information, you put in dollars to buy Bi=
tcoin, you sell Bitcoin to get dollars, and the exchange is the doorway bet=
ween the dollar financial system and the Bitcoin financial system.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a fraught business for the exchange to=
 be in. On one side, the side where it is making and accepting fiat payment=
s, it is connected to a regulated banking system, and in the US and many ot=
her countries banks have obligations to prevent financial crime. The banks =
have know-your-customer/anti-money-laundering obligations; they try to know=
 who their customers are and where their money comes from and what it=E2=80=
=99s being used for, to try to prevent it being used for crime. In practice=
, this often means that banks and credit card companies won=E2=80=99t let y=
ou send money to a crypto exchange unless the crypto exchange is itself reg=
ulated by national authorities and does its own KYC/AML checks to prevent i=
ts customers from using crypto for crime.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But on the other side, the side where it is tr=
ading crypto, the exchange is connected to the crypto system, and obviously=
 the exchange has lots of customers who have lots of reasons for using that=
 system, but, again, <em>one </em>important=C2=A0use case is crime. Presuma=
bly the people who want to use Bitcoin for crime will not actually be custo=
mers of an upstanding regulated exchange that does lots of KYC/AML, but the=
y will want to be customers of=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>exchange. There is a=
 lot of customer demand for a crypto exchange that is crime-friendly. If yo=
u set up a crypto exchange with the goal of being crime-friendly, and you d=
evelop a reputation for being crime-friendly, you will win a lot of busines=
s.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course there are problems. One is: The whol=
e point of this business is that your crypto exchange has to be able to get=
 money from banks and send money back to banks, and how are you going to co=
nvince banks to connect=C2=A0to your exchange? Most banks in the US and man=
y other countries want to deal with regulated crypto exchanges with good KY=
C/AML policies. You need to walk a fine line; you need to have a reputation=
=C2=A0<em>among customers=C2=A0</em>for being crime-friendly but a reputati=
on=C2=A0<em>among bankers=C2=A0</em>for stopping crime.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other problem is of course that <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30300607.279512/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMTgvY3J5cHRvLWV4Y2hhbmd=
lLWJpdHpsYXRvLWZvdW5kZXItYXJyZXN0ZWQtZm9yLW1vbmV5LWxhdW5kZXJpbmc_Y21waWQ9Qk=
JEMDExOTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0Z=
XImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTE5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBe7b59d90" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  you=E2=80=99ll eventually get arrested</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A Russian national was charged with money laun=
dering through a cryptocurrency exchange that allegedly masked the proceeds=
 of illegal gambling and drug deals valued at more than $700 million, as th=
e US goes after criminal suspects in the digital space.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anatoly Legkodymov, founder of the crypto exch=
ange Bitzlato, was arrested Tuesday in Miami, the Justice Department said a=
t a press conference Wednesday. Hong Kong-registered Bitzlato was a =E2=80=
=9Ccritical financial resource=E2=80=9D for the Hydra dark web market, the =
largest and longest-running such marketplace, Deputy Attorney General Lisa =
Monaco said at the conference. The dark web traffics in illicit goods and s=
ervices.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bitzlato processed illegal funds including mil=
lions of dollars in ransomware gains, according to a Justice Department sta=
tement. Legkodymov, 40, who lives in Shenzhen, China, and in Russia, posted=
 on an internal chat that Bitzlato users were =E2=80=9Cknown to be crooks,=
=E2=80=9D according to the US. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Monaco summed up the Bitzlato-Hydra connection=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The two =E2=80=9Cformed a high-tech axis of cr=
yptocrime,=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9CHydra buyers funded illicit purchase=
s =E2=80=94 of illegal drugs, stolen financial information, and hacking ser=
vices =E2=80=94 from crypto accounts hosted at Bitzlato, and sellers of the=
se illegal goods and services at Hydra sent criminal proceeds to accounts a=
t Bitzlato.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/30300607.279512/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3YvdXNh=
by1lZG55L3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvZmlsZS8xNTYyOTk2L2Rvd25sb2Fk/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cBfa373809" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;"> criminal complaint</a>. I often find myself writi=
ng about criminal and regulatory cases against financial institutions, and =
sometimes those cases will quote colorful emails and chat messages that peo=
ple at those financial institutions wrote in the course of doing alleged cr=
imes, and those emails and chats will often be pretty funny, but they will =
have the tone of =E2=80=9Ccan=E2=80=99t believe we=E2=80=99re doing this, h=
ope we don=E2=80=99t go to jail.=E2=80=9D Because they are doing crimes at =
a basically law-abiding company; they feel nervous and out of place about t=
he crime that they are doing.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At Bitzlato, the business was allegedly crime,=
 so there are just a lot of very matter-of-fact customer-support chats wher=
e customers ask for support doing crimes and Bitzlato supports them. The co=
mplaint quotes some:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On or about December 27, 2017, a user with the=
 username =E2=80=9CDude Weed=E2=80=9D wrote to Bitzlato=E2=80=99s customer =
service portal, stating: =E2=80=9CI have a bitcoin wallet in my account on =
the Hydra site. I also have a wallet here . . . How do I recharge a Hydra w=
allet=E2=80=9D? The user also provided transaction details. Based on my tra=
ining and experience, this query reflects the user=E2=80=99s desire to send=
 funds from Bitzlato to Hydra. A Bitzlato representative responded: =E2=80=
=9CHello dude weed,=E2=80=9D apologized for the delay in the transaction, a=
nd stated that =E2=80=9CThe transaction successfully went online.=E2=80=9D =
...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On or about May 5, 2021, a user asked whether =
he could =E2=80=9Cexchange dirty bitcoin for Sber without problems here=E2=
=80=9D=E2=80=94an apparent reference to Sberbank, a Russian bank. A Bitzlat=
o representative asked the user to clarify, and he wrote: =E2=80=9CWell for=
 example the person sent me to my wallet bitcoins taken from darknet, some =
kind of illegal exchanges, as far as I know they automatically get to dirty=
 bitcoins. So my question is, when I transfer them to Sberbank in rubles, c=
an I change them?=E2=80=9D The Bitzlato representative responded that =E2=
=80=9CIn this case there are no limitations from the service in this matter=
.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nobody is like =E2=80=9Clol dude weed, hope yo=
u don=E2=80=99t get busted for buying drugs online from a dark web marketpl=
ace!=E2=80=9D Of course Dude Weed was buying drugs online from a dark web m=
arketplace; why else would he be there? And:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On or about April 23, 2019, Execut=
ive-1 again warned his colleagues, including [Legkodymov], that =E2=80=9Cbi=
tzlato clients are addicts who buy drugs at the hydra site and=C2=A0similar=
 resources.=E2=80=9D LEGKODYMOV responded that Bitzlato could expand by off=
ering anonymous financial services to run-of-the-mill individuals, such as =
taxi drivers.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly, Bitzlato <em>had=C2=A0</em>KYC/AML =
procedures, since you need those to connect to the banking system, but it w=
ould be bad customer service to insist on following them, so Bitzlato custo=
mer support was allegedly pretty chill about them:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On December 17, 2020, a Bitzlato representativ=
e asked a user to provide his identity documents. The user protested, writi=
ng, =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t quite understand why you need a photo of this =
card? It=E2=80=99s not mine[.]=E2=80=9D In further conversations, the user =
clarified that =E2=80=9Ceveryone on the site trades with other people=E2=80=
=99s cards . . . they often discuss so-called =E2=80=98drops.=E2=80=99=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0The user commented that he had been told to create an account u=
sing credentials supplied by an online cryptocurrency training course that =
he had found on Instagram. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On or about May 7, 2022, a Bitzlato user was a=
sked to provide his identifying information. The user responded that he was=
 =E2=80=9Cnot going to lie to you and tell you tales[.] I bought this accou=
nt=E2=80=94bought it, I=E2=80=99m telling you.=E2=80=9D The user added that=
 there were =E2=80=9Chundreds of these accounts with passed verifications=
=E2=80=94as if you didn=E2=80=99t know that.=E2=80=9D ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On or about September 12, 2022, Bitzlato block=
ed a user=E2=80=99s account and asked him to verify his identity. The user =
responded that he would provide =E2=80=9Ca woman=E2=80=99s=E2=80=9D identit=
y documents, adding: =E2=80=9CAm I an idiot to verify myself? Verify the =
=E2=80=98drop.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D The user added that he would be transferri=
ng ransomware proceeds and =E2=80=9Ca payment from Hydra=E2=80=9D to his Bi=
tzlato account. The Bitzlato customer service representative responded that=
 an account verified in the name of the user=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cdrop,=E2=80=
=9D or straw man, would =E2=80=9Cbelong to your drop,=E2=80=9D and conclude=
d: =E2=80=9COkay, we are waiting for the application.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CDrop=E2=80=9D is apparently Russian s=
lang for a straw man: You have someone with a clean record set up a Bitzlat=
o account, then you sell that account to someone who wants to do crime. And=
:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">LEGKODYMOV was also aware that Bit=
zlato=E2=80=99s customers were not using the service under their true ident=
ities. On or about May 29, 2019 LEGKODYMOV wrote to a colleague in a chat: =
=E2=80=9CAll traders are known to be crooks. Trading on =E2=80=98drops,=E2=
=80=99 etc. You do realize that they all (I think 90%) do not trade on thei=
r [identity] cards.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At some point Bitzlato=E2=80=99s marketing dir=
ector allegedly made a document called =E2=80=9CCompetitor Analysis=E2=80=
=9D that described Bitzlato=E2=80=99s pros and cons:</p>
