<![endif]-->
</div><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Just perfect marketing, really, for a cr=
ime-friendly crypto exchange. The main pros are (1) it=E2=80=99s fine with =
crime and (2) you can deposit money easily. The main cons are (1) it=E2=80=
=99s fine with crime, (2) so crime will probably be done to you, and (3) it=
=E2=80=99s expensive to=C2=A0<em>withdraw=C2=A0</em>money.<a class=3D"footn=
ote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: n=
one !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bor=
der-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important=
; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The weird thing about this case is that=C2=A0B=
itzlato appears to be basically a Russian crypto exchange for Russian users=
 to buy and sell Bitcoin in Russia using Russian rubles without giving Bitz=
lato their Russian identity cards, and now it is being prosecuted <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30300607.279512/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3YvdXNhby1lZG55L3ByL2ZvdW5kZXItYW5kLW1ham9yaXR5LW93bmVy=
LWJpdHpsYXRvLWNyeXB0b2N1cnJlbmN5LWV4Y2hhbmdlLWNoYXJnZWQtdW5saWNlbnNlZC1tb25=
leQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4aaee379" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> in Brooklyn</a>. It was hea=
dquartered in Hong Kong, and Legkodymov apparently logged on a few times to=
 run it from Miami, but it seems to have been mostly Russian and had minima=
l involvement with the US financial system. Minimal, but enough:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Moreover, Bitzlato=E2=80=99s custo=
mer service representatives have repeatedly advised users that they were pe=
rmitted to transact with the United States. On or about December 16, 2020, =
for example, a user asked whether he could =E2=80=9Cuse American bank cards=
 to buy and sell [cryptocurrency].=E2=80=9D A Bitzlato representative repli=
ed: =E2=80=9CYes, of course. Choose USD=C2=A0currency in =E2=80=98Preferenc=
es.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Similarly, on January 20, 2021, a Bitzlato user asked=
 whether he could =E2=80=9Cget money from the U.S. to this wallet.=E2=80=9D=
 A Bitzlato representative replied: =E2=80=9CYou can transfer funds from an=
ywhere in the world.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in fact, Bitzlato=C2=A0<em>helped US law e=
nforcement with inquiries into crime:</em></p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In response to requests for accoun=
t data from U.S. law enforcement agents about specific users who were the s=
ubjects of law enforcement investigations, Bitzlato personnel provided char=
ts that reflected the Internet Protocol addresses from which those users we=
re logging into Bitzlato=E2=80=99s servers. Those charts included a column =
titled =E2=80=9Cuser_ip_country,=E2=80=9D reflecting the country in which e=
ach IP address appeared to be located. In numerous instances, the Bitzlato =
charts reflected that users were accessing Bitzlato=E2=80=99s servers from =
the United States, including logins from an IP address located in Brooklyn,=
 New York that was identified in October 2022.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So, not entirely pro-crime. But the complaint =
doesn=E2=80=99t actually say that Bitzlato supported any crime in the US, t=
hat anyone in the US used Bitzlato to buy Bitcoin to buy drugs or to sell B=
itcoin received in ransoms. Nor does it say that it supported any dollar-li=
nked crime, that any Russian hackers used Bitzlato to turn Bitcoin ransoms =
into dollars. Mostly it says that Bitzlato allowed Russian customers to tra=
de rubles for crypto without using their Russian identity cards, and that i=
t had a website that you could access from the US. US prosecutors are in th=
e business of prosecuting financial crime anywhere in the world, and if Rus=
sians are hiding their transactions from the Russian government, US prosecu=
tors are interested.</p>
